Twitter US Airline Sentiment Analysis¶

Domain:¶

Airline

Description:¶

Modern social media allows users to share their personal views, opinions and experiences. This is a great source of information and it allows us to decide what services we want to use and what to expect from certain companies. It is also especially important to businesses like airline companies in order to stay competitive and potentially use this data to improve the quality of their services.

Attributes Information:¶

A sentiment analysis job about the problems of each major U.S. airline. Twitter data was scraped from February of 2015 and contributors were asked to first classify positive, negative, and neutral tweets, followed by categorizing negative reasons (such as "late flight" or "rude service").

Link to the Kaggle project site: https://www.kaggle.com/crowdflower/twitter-airline-sentiment

  • tweet_id: The id of the tweet.
  • airline_sentiment: Sentiment classification: "neutral", "positive", or "negative".
  • airline_sentiment_confidence: Sentiment confidence score.
  • negativereason: If sentiment was negative, the reason categorization: "Late Flight", "Lost Luggage" etc.
  • negativereason_confidence: Negative reason confedence scrore.
  • airline: Airline name.
  • name: User name.
  • retweet_count: Number of retweets.
  • text: Tweet content.
  • tweet_created: Date/Time of the tweet.
  • tweet_coord: Longitude and latitude of the user location.
  • tweet_location: Location name.
  • user_timezone: Location timezone.

Objective:¶

Analyze how travelers in February 2015 expressed their feelings on Twitter and build a model for sentiment classification using the techniques learnt as a part of the course.

Steps and tasks¶

  1. Libraries & Dataset Import
  2. EDA

sent_palette=['tomato', 'steelblue', 'mediumseagreen', 'khaki', 'plum', 'lightseagreen']
sent_cmap = matplotlib.colors.ListedColormap(sent_palette)

def plot_counts_percentages(data, col, vr=0, pal=sent_palette):
    total_items = data.shape[0]
    chart = sns.countplot(data[col], order = data[col].value_counts().index, palette=pal);
    chart.set(title=col.title(), xlabel='', ylabel='Count')
    chart.set_xticklabels(chart.get_xticklabels(),  rotation=vr)
    for p in chart.patches:
        height = p.get_height()
        chart.text(p.get_x() + p.get_width()/2., height + 4, '{:1.2f}'.format((height/total_items)*100), ha='center')

4. Text pre-processing. Data preparation.¶

Definning & Testing Pre-processing Functions¶

As we will need to implement several pre-processing steps and repeat them on the testing dataset, we will create our functions one by one and then form a pipeline function that will incapsulate all of them.

  • Remove HTML tags

As far as the simple search goes, there is no HTML tags in the tweets in this dataset. However we will implement this step for complitness and because it is a requirement.

In [295]:
def strip_html_tags(text):
    soup = BeautifulSoup(text, "html.parser")
    stripped_text = soup.get_text()
    return stripped_text
In [296]:
strip_html_tags('<li id="notebook_tour" title=""><a href="#">A quick tour of the notebook user interface</a></li>')
Out[296]:
'A quick tour of the notebook user interface'
  • Remove the numbers
In [297]:
def remove_numbers(text):
    return re.sub(r'\d+', '', text)
In [298]:
remove_numbers('@AmericanAir 767 seconds from touchdown at Madrid airport in April 2013')
Out[298]:
'@AmericanAir  seconds from touchdown at Madrid airport in April '
  • Remove non-ASCII / accented characters
In [299]:
def remove_non_ascii(text):
    return unicodedata.normalize('NFKD', text).encode('ascii', 'ignore').decode('utf-8', 'ignore')
In [300]:
remove_non_ascii('@SouthwestAir Plz Sm ccntd txt to #AA for  the KC  OKC directs.')
Out[300]:
'@SouthwestAir Plz Some Accented text to #AA for Ys the KC ai  OKC directs.'
  • Remove special characters & punctuation
In [301]:
def remove_special_and_punctuation(text):
    return re.sub(r'[^\w\s]', '', text) # [a-zA-Z0-9_] & [ \t\n\r\f\v]
In [302]:
remove_special_and_punctuation('@SouthwestAir (where) are our / pilots? Plane! is here flight says it\'s still on time, but we should of been off the ground 15 minutes ago.')
Out[302]:
'SouthwestAir where are our  pilots Plane is here flight says its still on time but we should of been off the ground 15 minutes ago'
  • Convert to lowercase
In [303]:
def to_lowercase(text):
    return text.lower()
In [304]:

Out[304]:

  • Removal of the URLs
In [305]:
def remove_urls(text):
    return re.sub(r'http\S+', '', text)
In [306]:

Out[306]:

  • Replace contractions
In [307]:
def replace_contractions(text):
    return contractions.fix(text)
In [308]:
replace_contractions('@VirginAmerica  I applied over 2 needn\t, shan, shan\'t weeks ago. Haven\'t heard back and I\'m flying this week #disappointed')
Out[308]:
'@VirginAmerica  I applied over 2 needn\t, shan, shall not weeks ago. have not heard back and I am flying this week #disappointed'
  • Remove emails
In [309]:
def remove_emails(text):
    return re.sub(r'[a-z0-9\.\-+_]+@[a-z0-9\.\-+_]+\.[a-z]+', '', text)
In [310]:
remove_emails('@AmericanAir and feel free to email me mikehertz7@gmail.com - don\'t worry, we\'re not going anywhere')
Out[310]:
"@AmericanAir and feel free to email me  - don't worry, we're not going anywhere"
  • Remove tagged Twitter entities
In this excercise we are going to use techniques that do not capture any natural language constructs like nouns or proverbs or verbs. Hence entities like company or user names won't bring us any value for the purpose of sentiment analisys. In the tweets they are marked by @ symbol and look like @AmericanAir @justynmoro for example. We will remove them, but we should be careful as @ symbol may be cleared by our other filtering functions. Hence this step should be taken before them and also we should remove emails first.
In [311]:
def remove_tweeter_entities(text):
    return re.sub(r'@[A-Za-z]+', '', text)
In [312]:
remove_tweeter_entities('@AmericanAir @justynmoro I totally agree. Lousy service!')
Out[312]:
'  I totally agree. Lousy service!'
  • Remove stop words

Stop words are a set of commonly used words in a language. Examples of stop words in English are 'a', 'the', 'is', 'are' etc. The rational behind removing the stop words is that we can focus on the important words instead.

In our current approach we will do contractions first and then remove the stopwords. This means we will transform words like shouldn't to should not first. And then we will remove words like should, however we should remember that words like no or not are important for sentiment alalysis, so we need to keep them.

Let us compose our custom stopword list.

In [313]:
full_stopword_list = stopwords.words('english')
retain_stopword_list = [ 'no', 'not']

custom_stopwords = list(set(full_stopword_list) - set(retain_stopword_list))
In [314]:
def remove_stopwords(words):
    return [word for word in words if word not in custom_stopwords]
In [315]:
remove_stopwords(['Test', 'not', 'no', 'should', 'like', 'will', 'is'])
Out[315]:
['Test', 'not', 'no', 'like']
  • Tokenization
In [316]:
def tokenize(text):
    return word_tokenize(text)

  • Stemming

Stemming is the process of reducing inflection in words (e.g. running, runs) to their root form (e.g. run). The 'root' in this case may not be a real root word, but just a canonical form of the original word.

In [318]:
def stem_words(words):
    stemmer = LancasterStemmer()
    return [stemmer.stem(word) for word in words]
In [319]:
stem_words(tokenize('Stemming is the process of reducing inflection in words running runs'))
Out[319]:
['stem',
 'is',
 'the',
 'process',
 'of',
 'reduc',
 'inflect',
 'in',
 'word',
 'run',
 'run']
  • Lemmatization

Lemmatization is very similar to the stemming, it removes inflections by mapping a word to its root form. The only difference is that lemmatization actually transforms words to the actual root. For example, the word 'better' would map to 'good'. NLTK provides WordNetLemmatizer class which is a thin wrapper around the wordnet corpus.

In [320]:
def lemmatize_words(words):
    lemmatizer = WordNetLemmatizer()
    return [lemmatizer.lemmatize(word, pos='v') for word in words]
In [321]:
lemmatize_words(tokenize('Stemming is the process of reducing inflection in words running runs'))
Out[321]:
['Stemming',
 'be',
 'the',
 'process',
 'of',
 'reduce',
 'inflection',
 'in',
 'word',
 'run',
 'run']

Building Normalization Function & Testing¶

In [322]:
def normalize_text(text):
    clean_text = strip_html_tags(text)                        # Remove HTML tags (<b>Text</b> -> Text)
    clean_text = to_lowercase(clean_text)                     # Convert to lower case (BOB -> bob)
    clean_text = remove_emails(clean_text)                    # Remove emails (bob@domain.com)
    clean_text = remove_tweeter_entities(clean_text)          # Remove Tweetter entities (@Bob)
    clean_text = remove_urls(clean_text)                      # Remove URLs (http://domain.com/path)
    clean_text = replace_contractions(clean_text)             # Replace contractions (haven't -> have not)
    clean_text = remove_non_ascii(clean_text)                 # Replace contractions (ccntd -> Accented, '' -> '')
    clean_text = remove_special_and_punctuation(clean_text)   # Remove special chars & punctuation (',' -> '')
    clean_text = remove_numbers(clean_text)                   # Remove numbers ('123' -> '')
    
    return remove_stopwords(tokenize(clean_text))             # Tokenize and Remove stopwords
  • Clean text - Test

Insights:

  • As we can see we were able to apply all our cleaning functions on the input document, tokenize, remove stop words using our custom list. Finally we tried Stemming and Lemmatization, the later gave us more human readable output, so let us proceed with Lemmatization and prepare our corpus for vectorization.
  • Order of how we apply our functions is important.

5. Vectorization¶

  • CountVectorizer

CountVectorizer converts a collection of text documents to a matrix of token counts. We will keep only 1000 features as the number of features will not only increase the processing time, but can cause the Curse of dimensionality.

In [332]:
cv_vectorizer = CountVectorizer(analyzer='word', tokenizer=None, preprocessor=None, stop_words=None, max_features=1000)

# fit_transform() does two things:
# - First, it fits the model and learns the vocabulary;
# - Second, it transforms our training data into feature vectors.
# The input to fit_transform should be a list of strings.
train_cv_lemm_features = cv_vectorizer.fit_transform(X_train.to_list())
train_cv_lemm_features = train_cv_lemm_features.toarray()

  • TfidfVectorizer

TfidfVectorizer converts a collection of raw documents to a matrix of TF-IDF features. It will give less importance to the most frequent words and also considers less frequent words. We will go with the same assumptions as before and use 1000 features.

6. Build, Fit and Evaluate Models¶

In [336]:
from sklearn.model_selection import cross_val_score, KFold
from sklearn.metrics import classification_report, confusion_matrix

def evaluate_classifier(classifier, Xtrain, Ytrain, Xtest, Ytest, data):
    classifier.fit(Xtrain, Ytrain)
    
    training_accuracy = classifier.score(Xtrain, Ytrain)
    testing_accuracy = classifier.score(Xtest, Ytest)

    # Print Report
    print(f'Training accuracy  : {training_accuracy:0.4f}')
    print(f'Testing accuracy   : {testing_accuracy:0.4f}')

    # Confusion Matrix
    y_pred = classifier.predict(Xtest)
    y_test_labels = lb_encoder.inverse_transform(Ytest)
    y_pred_labels = lb_encoder.inverse_transform(y_pred)
    
    cm = confusion_matrix(Ytest, y_pred)
    print(cm)
    
    # Plot Confusion Matrix
    labels_list = np.unique(data['airline_sentiment']);
    df_cm = pd.DataFrame(cm, index = [i for i in labels_list], columns = [i for i in labels_list])

    plt.figure(figsize=(5, 5))
    heatmap=sns.heatmap(df_cm, annot=True, cmap='Greens', fmt='d', cbar=False) # mako, YlOrBr, Blues
    heatmap.set_xticklabels(heatmap.get_xticklabels(), rotation=45)
    heatmap.set_yticklabels(heatmap.get_yticklabels(), rotation=0)
    plt.ylabel('Actual')
    plt.xlabel('Predicted')
    plt.show()
  
    # classification_report
    print(classification_report(y_test_labels, y_pred_labels))

7. Summary¶

After loading and describing data we moved stright forward to our objective of applying our NLP skills for the task of tweet sentimet classification.

Pre-Processing

  • While working with text it is important to clean it up, remove "noise". For example, for our task of sentiment analysis and classification, it would make no sense to include HTML tags. The same would go towards emails, web site urls, numbers and other specific entities which do not have any sentiment aspect. We have also implemented other common pre-processing techniques such as converitng to lower case, replacing/removing non ASCII characters, punctuation and contractions. Finally we removed the stop words keeping only those which are important for the sentiments, like "no" or "not". Also it is important to apply some cleaning functions in a specific order to avoid interference.
  • After tokenization and stop word removal we still have an opportunity to reduce the number of dimentions/features by reducing different forms of words to their basic/root form. We implemented both common techniques Stemming and Lemmatization, but went forward with Lemmatization for its natural form of root words. Speed implications did not concerned us here as we don't have a large dataset.

Vectorization

  • Text is unstructured data and cannot be used as it is. In oreder to convert it into structured form we used Count and Tf-idf vectorizers. Count Vectorizer would just count the frequency of the words in each document for all the documents, giving no special weightage to any of the words. Tf-idf Vectorizer, on the other hand, will calculate each word occurrence count and divide it by inverse document matrix. It reduces the impact of words that occur very frequently, hence offering little to none in terms of information. One example of such words will be the word "flight", it is pretty common across all the documents (tweets) in the corpus, but brings no useful information for our task.

Modeling results

  • We built and tuned two models using RandomForestClassifier on our vectorizer's results.
  • As we can see both models (based on count & tf-idf vectorizers) give us vertually the same results. However it worth noticing that model based on tf-idf inputs tends to overfit more quickly.
  • Initial imbalance in the data towards negative sentiment biases our models. Looking at our evaluation printed above we can see precision/recall/f1-score are all the hihgest for negative class. Also neutrual and positive classes are more often mistaken for negative.
  • With the current sets of features we can reach testing accuracy in the range of ~0.74 - 0.78 on both vectorizers. However to get to 0.78 models will overfit significantly going up to 0.99 on the training set. Hence for our best results we chose the parameters that gave us ~0.75 - 0.76 in accuracy without significat overfitting. Error Rate is ~0.24 - 0.25.
  • One of the most noticable problems though with the current approach is that we are not capturing any sequences. Our model will not understand nouns, verbs, adjectives... no concept of ordering "a b c" or words' relatioship which are inherently important to the natural language processing. Our input data is frequency based and not sequence based.
  • Reccomendations on the improvment would be to try LSTM model and also work on feature enginering further, for instance we could do the spell checking and hence reduce the number of features, or we could have processed emoji which would give as a unique insight into the tweets that have them.

Dispite the fact that our model cannot detect neutral or positive sentiments very well it still can be used to detect majority of negative tweets. That on it's own can be a valuable source of information used by airlines for services improvement.
